const SEC_SPRING = {
  id:"springboot",title:"Spring Boot",icon:"🌿",ib:"rgba(74,222,128,.12)",ic:"#4ade80",
  grp:"spring",bar:"#4ade80",tglow:"rgba(74,222,128,.07)",
  desc:"Auto-configuration, DI, AOP, Security, Actuator, Config Server, Profiles, Validation & more.",
  tags:["Auto-config","DI/IoC","AOP","Security","Config Server","Actuator"],
  qs:[
    {q:"How does Spring Boot auto-configuration work internally?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-auto-configuration",
     a:"<code>@SpringBootApplication</code> includes <code>@EnableAutoConfiguration</code>, which triggers <code>AutoConfigurationImportSelector</code>. It reads all class names from <code>META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports</code> (one per line).<br><br>Each auto-configuration class is annotated with conditional annotations:<ul><li><code>@ConditionalOnClass</code> — only activate if a certain class is on the classpath</li><li><code>@ConditionalOnMissingBean</code> — only if the developer hasn't already defined one</li><li><code>@ConditionalOnProperty</code> — only if a config property has a specific value</li></ul><br><strong>Debug tip:</strong> run with <code>--debug</code> to see the Conditions Evaluation Report — shows exactly which configurations were applied and which were skipped, and why.<br><br><strong>Example — custom auto-configuration class:</strong><br><pre>@AutoConfiguration\n@ConditionalOnClass(DataSource.class)\n@ConditionalOnProperty(name = \"app.audit.enabled\", havingValue = \"true\", matchIfMissing = true)\npublic class AuditAutoConfiguration {\n\n  @Bean\n  @ConditionalOnMissingBean\n  public AuditService auditService() {\n    return new DefaultAuditService();\n  }\n}\n// Register in: META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports</pre>"},

    {q:"Explain the Spring Bean lifecycle end-to-end.",d:"medium",id:"spring-bean-lifecycle-end",
     a:"<strong>Creation phase:</strong><ol><li>Instantiation — constructor invoked</li><li>Dependency injection — setter/field injection</li><li>Aware callbacks — <code>BeanNameAware.setBeanName()</code>, <code>ApplicationContextAware.setApplicationContext()</code></li><li><code>BeanPostProcessor.postProcessBeforeInitialization()</code> (all registered processors)</li><li><code>@PostConstruct</code> method / <code>InitializingBean.afterPropertiesSet()</code> / custom <code>init-method</code></li><li><code>BeanPostProcessor.postProcessAfterInitialization()</code> — this is where AOP proxies are created</li><li>Bean is fully initialised and ready</li></ol><br><strong>Destruction phase (on context close):</strong><ol><li><code>@PreDestroy</code> method</li><li><code>DisposableBean.destroy()</code></li><li>Custom <code>destroy-method</code></li></ol><br><br><strong>Example — all lifecycle hooks in one bean:</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class LifecycleDemo implements BeanNameAware, InitializingBean, DisposableBean {\n\n  @Override\n  public void setBeanName(String name) {\n    System.out.println(\"Bean name set: \" + name); // Aware callback\n  }\n\n  @PostConstruct\n  public void postConstruct() { System.out.println(\"@PostConstruct\"); }\n\n  @Override\n  public void afterPropertiesSet() { System.out.println(\"InitializingBean\"); }\n\n  @PreDestroy\n  public void preDestroy() { System.out.println(\"@PreDestroy\"); }\n\n  @Override\n  public void destroy() { System.out.println(\"DisposableBean.destroy()\"); }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"What is @Transactional propagation? Explain REQUIRED, REQUIRES_NEW, and NESTED.",d:"hard",id:"transactional-propagation-required-requi",
     a:"Propagation defines how a transactional method behaves when called from within an existing transaction.<br><br><strong>REQUIRED</strong> (default): joins an existing transaction if one is active; creates a new one if not. Rollback in the inner method rolls back the outer transaction too.<br><br><strong>REQUIRES_NEW:</strong> always suspends any active transaction and starts a fresh, independent one. The inner transaction commits or rolls back independently. Use for: audit logging, notifications — things that must persist even if the outer transaction rolls back.<br><br><strong>NESTED:</strong> creates a savepoint within the outer transaction. Inner can rollback to the savepoint without rolling back the entire outer transaction. Only works with JDBC connections that support savepoints.<br><br><strong>Critical pitfall:</strong> Spring implements <code>@Transactional</code> via AOP proxy. Self-invocation (calling a transactional method from <em>within the same bean</em>) bypasses the proxy — transaction does NOT start. Always call transactional methods from a <em>different</em> bean.<br><br><strong>Example — REQUIRED calling REQUIRES_NEW (audit survives outer rollback):</strong><br><pre>@Service\npublic class OrderService {\n  @Autowired AuditService audit;\n\n  @Transactional                    // REQUIRED: joins or creates tx\n  public void placeOrder(Order order) {\n    orderRepo.save(order);\n    audit.log(\"ORDER_PLACED\", order.getId()); // inner tx commits independently\n    if (order.isFraudulent()) throw new FraudException(); // outer rolls back\n  }\n}\n\n@Service\npublic class AuditService {\n  @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)\n  public void log(String event, Long id) {\n    auditRepo.save(new AuditLog(event, id)); // committed even if outer rolls back\n  }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"What is Spring AOP? Explain Aspect, Advice, Pointcut, and JoinPoint.",d:"medium",id:"spring-aop-aspect-advice",
     a:"AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) extracts cross-cutting concerns (logging, security, transactions, caching, retry) out of business logic.<br><br><strong>Aspect:</strong> the module encapsulating the cross-cutting concern — a class annotated with <code>@Aspect</code>.<br><br><strong>JoinPoint:</strong> a specific point in program execution where advice can be applied — in Spring AOP, always a <em>method execution</em>.<br><br><strong>Pointcut:</strong> an expression that selects which join points to advise. Example: <code>execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))</code>.<br><br><strong>Advice:</strong> the action to take at a matched join point:<ul><li><code>@Before</code> — runs before method</li><li><code>@AfterReturning</code> — runs after successful return</li><li><code>@AfterThrowing</code> — runs on exception</li><li><code>@After</code> — runs always (finally)</li><li><code>@Around</code> — wraps the method; most powerful, must call <code>proceed()</code></li></ul><br>Spring uses JDK dynamic proxies (interface-based) or CGLIB (class-based). Cannot proxy <code>final</code> classes or private methods.<br><br><strong>Example — @Aspect with @Around advice:</strong><br><pre>@Aspect\n@Component\npublic class TimingAspect {\n\n  @Pointcut(\"execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))\")\n  public void serviceMethods() {}\n\n  @Around(\"serviceMethods()\")\n  public Object time(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp) throws Throwable {\n    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();\n    try {\n      return pjp.proceed();               // invoke the real method\n    } finally {\n      log.info(\"{} took {}ms\", pjp.getSignature(),\n               System.currentTimeMillis() - start);\n    }\n  }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"How does Spring Cloud Config Server work and how do clients refresh config?",d:"medium",id:"spring-cloud-config-server",
     a:"<strong>Config Server</strong> centralises externalised configuration for all microservices. It serves config from a Git repo, filesystem, or HashiCorp Vault.<br><br><strong>File resolution order</strong> (later overrides earlier):<ol><li><code>application.yml</code> — defaults for all services</li><li><code>{service}.yml</code> — service-specific</li><li><code>{service}-{profile}.yml</code> — service + profile</li></ol><br><strong>Client bootstrap:</strong> add to <code>application.yml</code>:<br><code>spring.config.import: configserver:http://config-server:8888</code><br>Config is fetched before the application context starts.<br><br><strong>Live refresh:</strong><ul><li>Change config in Git and push</li><li>POST to <code>/actuator/refresh</code> on the target instance — reloads <code>@RefreshScope</code> beans</li><li>Use Spring Cloud Bus (Kafka/RabbitMQ) to broadcast refresh to ALL instances at once</li></ul><br>Encrypt secrets in Git using <code>/encrypt</code> endpoint; Config Server decrypts on serve.<br><br><strong>Client application.yml:</strong><br><pre>spring:\n  application:\n    name: order-service\n  config:\n    import: \"configserver:http://config-server:8888\"\n  cloud:\n    config:\n      fail-fast: true</pre><br><strong>@RefreshScope bean (reloads on POST /actuator/refresh):</strong><br><pre>@RefreshScope\n@Service\npublic class FeatureService {\n  @Value(\"${features.newCheckout:false}\")\n  private boolean newCheckout;\n\n  public boolean isNewCheckoutEnabled() { return newCheckout; }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"What are Spring Boot Actuator endpoints and how do you secure them?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-actuator-endpoints",
     a:"Actuator exposes production-ready management endpoints over HTTP (or JMX).<br><br><strong>Key endpoints:</strong><ul><li><code>/actuator/health</code> — UP/DOWN with component details. Kubernetes maps this to liveness/readiness probes</li><li><code>/actuator/metrics</code> — Micrometer metrics (request rate, error rate, JVM stats)</li><li><code>/actuator/env</code> — active config properties (sensitive!)</li><li><code>/actuator/loggers</code> — change log levels at runtime without restart</li><li><code>/actuator/threaddump</code> — thread state snapshot for debugging</li><li><code>/actuator/heapdump</code> — download heap dump for memory analysis</li></ul><br><strong>Production security:</strong><ul><li>Expose only health/info publicly: <code>management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health,info</code></li><li>Put management on a separate internal port: <code>management.server.port=9090</code></li><li>Or secure with Spring Security — require authentication for <code>/actuator/**</code></li></ul><br><br><strong>application.yml — management config:</strong><br><pre>management:\n  server:\n    port: 9090\n  endpoints:\n    web:\n      exposure:\n        include: \"health,info,metrics,loggers\"\n  endpoint:\n    health:\n      show-details: when-authorized</pre><br><strong>Spring Security — restrict /actuator/**:</strong><br><pre>@Bean\nSecurityFilterChain actuatorSecurity(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {\n  return http\n    .securityMatcher(\"/actuator/**\")\n    .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth\n      .requestMatchers(\"/actuator/health\").permitAll()\n      .anyRequest().hasRole(\"OPS\"))\n    .httpBasic(Customizer.withDefaults())\n    .build();\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"How do you handle global exceptions in Spring Boot using RFC 7807?",d:"medium",id:"you-handle-global-exceptions",
     a:"<strong>@RestControllerAdvice</strong> + <code>@ExceptionHandler</code> intercepts exceptions thrown from any controller.<br><br><strong>Spring Boot 3 / Spring 6 — ProblemDetail</strong> (RFC 7807):<br><pre>@ExceptionHandler(OrderNotFoundException.class)\nProblemDetail handleNotFound(OrderNotFoundException ex) {\n  ProblemDetail pd = ProblemDetail\n    .forStatusAndDetail(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, ex.getMessage());\n  pd.setTitle(\"Order not found\");\n  pd.setProperty(\"orderId\", ex.getOrderId());\n  return pd;\n}</pre><br>Enable automatically: <code>spring.mvc.problemdetails.enabled=true</code><br><br><strong>For validation errors</strong> handle <code>MethodArgumentNotValidException</code>:<br><pre>@ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)\nResponseEntity&lt;?&gt; handleValidation(MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {\n  Map&lt;String, String&gt; errors = new LinkedHashMap&lt;&gt;();\n  ex.getBindingResult().getFieldErrors()\n    .forEach(e -&gt; errors.put(e.getField(), e.getDefaultMessage()));\n  return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(errors);\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"How does Spring Security JWT authentication work end-to-end?",d:"hard",id:"spring-security-jwt-authentication",
     a:"<strong>Login flow:</strong><ol><li>POST <code>/auth/login</code> with credentials</li><li>Validate against UserDetailsService + PasswordEncoder</li><li>Sign JWT: <code>header.payload.signature</code> using HMAC-SHA256 (symmetric) or RS256 (asymmetric)</li><li>Return access token (short TTL ~15min) + refresh token (longer TTL)</li></ol><br><strong>Authenticated request flow:</strong><ol><li>Client sends <code>Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;</code></li><li>Custom <code>OncePerRequestFilter</code> extracts token</li><li>Validate signature, expiry, issuer (<code>jjwt</code> or <code>spring-security-oauth2-resource-server</code>)</li><li>Parse claims (userId, roles); create <code>UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken</code></li><li>Set in <code>SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(...)</code></li><li>Spring's <code>AuthorizationFilter</code> checks permissions</li></ol><br><strong>Config:</strong> <code>sessionCreationPolicy(STATELESS)</code> — no HttpSession. Disable CSRF (safe for stateless APIs).<br><br><strong>Example — JWT filter (core of the authenticated request flow):</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class JwtAuthFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {\n\n  @Override\n  protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest req,\n      HttpServletResponse res, FilterChain chain)\n      throws ServletException, IOException {\n\n    String header = req.getHeader(\"Authorization\");\n    if (header == null || !header.startsWith(\"Bearer \")) {\n      chain.doFilter(req, res); return;\n    }\n    String token = header.substring(7);\n    Claims claims = jwtService.validate(token); // throws if invalid/expired\n    var auth = new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(\n      claims.getSubject(), null,\n      AuthorityUtils.commaSeparatedStringToAuthorityList(\n        claims.get(\"roles\", String.class)));\n    SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(auth);\n    chain.doFilter(req, res);\n  }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"How do you configure Spring Security 6+ using SecurityFilterChain? Explain the filter chain ordering.",d:"hard",id:"you-configure-spring-security",
     a:"<strong>Spring Security 6+ uses component-based configuration</strong> instead of the deprecated WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter pattern.<br><br><strong>SecurityFilterChain bean:</strong><br><pre>@Configuration\n@EnableWebSecurity\npublic class SecurityConfig {\n  @Bean\n  SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {\n    return http\n      .csrf(csrf -> csrf\n        .csrfTokenRepository(CookieCSrfTokenRepository.withHttpOnlyFalse()))\n      .cors(cors -> cors.configurationSource(corsConfigurationSource()))\n      .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth\n        .requestMatchers(\"/api/public/**\").permitAll()\n        .requestMatchers(\"/api/admin/**\").hasRole(\"ADMIN\")\n        .anyRequest().authenticated())\n      .sessionManagement(session -> session\n        .sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS))\n      .oauth2Login(Customizer.withDefaults())\n      .httpBasic(Customizer.withDefaults())\n      .build();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Filter chain execution order:</strong> Spring Security processes requests through ~15 filters in this sequence:<ol><li><strong>SecurityContextPersistenceFilter</strong> — loads SecurityContext from session/storage</li><li><strong>CsrfFilter</strong> — validates CSRF tokens for state-changing operations</li><li><strong>UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter</strong> — processes form login (POST /login)</li><li><strong>OAuth2LoginAuthenticationFilter</strong> — handles OAuth2/OIDC callback</li><li><strong>BasicAuthenticationFilter</strong> — processes HTTP Basic Auth header</li><li><strong>BearerTokenAuthenticationFilter</strong> — validates JWT from Authorization header</li><li><strong>AuthorizationFilter</strong> — enforces access control rules based on SecurityContext</li></ol><br><strong>Adding custom filters:</strong><br><pre>.addFilterBefore(new JwtAuthFilter(), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class)\n.addFilterAfter(new CustomAuditFilter(), AuthorizationFilter.class)</pre><br><strong>CORS configuration:</strong><br><pre>@Bean\nCorsConfigurationSource corsConfigurationSource() {\n  CorsConfiguration config = new CorsConfiguration();\n  config.setAllowedOrigins(List.of(\"https://app.example.com\"));\n  config.setAllowedMethods(List.of(\"GET\",\"POST\",\"PUT\",\"DELETE\"));\n  config.setAllowedHeaders(List.of(\"*\"));\n  config.setAllowCredentials(true);\n  UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource source = new UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource();\n  source.registerCorsConfiguration(\"/**\", config);\n  return source;\n}</pre><br><strong>CSRF considerations:</strong> disable for stateless APIs (<code>.csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())</code>) since there's no session; keep enabled for traditional server-rendered apps with sessions.<br><br><strong>Key migration notes from WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter:</strong><ul><li>No longer extend a class; use <code>@Bean SecurityFilterChain</code> instead</li><li>Lambda DSL is preferred over method chaining with <code>.and()</code></li><li>Multiple SecurityFilterChain beans can coexist with different <code>@Order</code> and <code>securityMatcher</code> patterns</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is the difference between @Bean and @Component?",d:"medium",id:"bean-component",
     a:"Both register beans in the Spring application context — they differ in <em>where</em> and <em>why</em> you use them.<br><br><strong>@Component</strong> (and stereotypes <code>@Service</code>, <code>@Repository</code>, <code>@Controller</code>):<ul><li>Placed on <em>your own</em> classes</li><li>Discovered via component scanning (<code>@ComponentScan</code>)</li><li><code>@Repository</code> additionally wraps JPA/JDBC exceptions into Spring's <code>DataAccessException</code> hierarchy</li></ul><br><strong>@Bean</strong> (inside a <code>@Configuration</code> class):<ul><li>Used for third-party classes you don't own (e.g., registering a <code>RestTemplate</code>, DataSource, ObjectMapper)</li><li>When bean creation requires complex conditional logic</li><li>When you need to call the constructor with specific arguments</li></ul><br><strong>Example:</strong><br><pre>@Configuration\nclass AppConfig {\n  @Bean\n  ObjectMapper objectMapper() {\n    return new ObjectMapper().registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n  }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"How do you implement caching in Spring Boot with Redis and TTL?",d:"medium",id:"you-implement-caching-spring",
     a:"<strong>Setup:</strong><ol><li>Add <code>spring-boot-starter-cache</code> + <code>spring-boot-starter-data-redis</code></li><li>Add <code>@EnableCaching</code> to a config class</li><li>Configure <code>RedisCacheManager</code> with TTL</li></ol><br><pre>@Bean\nRedisCacheManager cacheManager(RedisConnectionFactory cf) {\n  RedisCacheConfiguration config = RedisCacheConfiguration.defaultCacheConfig()\n    .entryTtl(Duration.ofMinutes(10))\n    .serializeValuesWith(RedisSerializationContext\n      .SerializationPair.fromSerializer(new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer()));\n  return RedisCacheManager.builder(cf).cacheDefaults(config).build();\n}</pre><br><strong>Annotations:</strong><ul><li><code>@Cacheable(\"products\")</code> — return from cache if present; else execute and cache</li><li><code>@CacheEvict(\"products\")</code> — invalidate on mutation</li><li><code>@CachePut(\"products\")</code> — always execute and update cache</li></ul><br><strong>Cache key:</strong> default is method args. Customise: <code>@Cacheable(key = \"#id\")</code>."},

    {q:"What are Spring Profiles and how do they interact with Config Server?",d:"easy",id:"spring-profiles-they-interact",
     a:"<strong>Profiles</strong> let you have environment-specific beans and configuration.<br><br><strong>Activate:</strong><ul><li>JVM arg: <code>-Dspring.profiles.active=prod</code></li><li>Env var: <code>SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod</code></li><li>In yml: <code>spring.profiles.active: prod</code></li></ul><br><strong>Profile-specific files:</strong> <code>application-prod.yml</code> overrides <code>application.yml</code> properties.<br><br><strong>Conditional beans:</strong><br><pre>@Bean @Profile(\"prod\")\nDataSource prodDataSource() { ... }\n\n@Bean @Profile(\"!prod\")\nDataSource h2DataSource() { ... }</pre><br><strong>With Config Server,</strong> the server applies the same layering — it serves <code>application.yml</code> → <code>{service}.yml</code> → <code>{service}-prod.yml</code>. Most-specific always wins.<br><br><strong>Default profile:</strong> active when no other profile is specified. Name it <code>default</code> in <code>application.yml</code> using <code>spring.profiles.default</code>."},

    {q:"What is @Async in Spring and how do you configure a custom thread pool for it?",d:"medium",id:"async-spring-you-configure",
     a:"<code>@Async</code> makes a method execute asynchronously in a Spring-managed thread pool. The calling thread returns immediately.<br><br><strong>Setup:</strong><ol><li>Add <code>@EnableAsync</code> to a <code>@Configuration</code> class</li><li>Annotate the method with <code>@Async</code></li><li>Return <code>void</code>, <code>Future&lt;T&gt;</code>, or <code>CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;</code></li></ol><br><strong>Custom executor:</strong><br><pre>@Bean(\"asyncExecutor\")\nExecutor asyncExecutor() {\n  ThreadPoolTaskExecutor ex = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();\n  ex.setCorePoolSize(5);\n  ex.setMaxPoolSize(20);\n  ex.setQueueCapacity(200);\n  ex.setThreadNamePrefix(\"async-\");\n  ex.setRejectedExecutionHandler(new ThreadPoolExecutor.CallerRunsPolicy());\n  ex.initialize();\n  return ex;\n}\n\n@Async(\"asyncExecutor\")\npublic CompletableFuture&lt;String&gt; processAsync() { ... }</pre><br><strong>Pitfall:</strong> <code>@Async</code> on a method called from within the <em>same</em> bean bypasses the proxy — no async execution. Always call from a different bean."},

    {q:"How does Spring Boot handle validation with Bean Validation (JSR-380)?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-handle-validation",
     a:"Spring Boot auto-configures Hibernate Validator (the JSR-380 reference implementation).<br><br><strong>Step 1 — annotate the DTO:</strong><br><pre>public record CreateOrderRequest(\n  @NotBlank(message = \"Customer ID required\")\n  String customerId,\n\n  @NotEmpty @Size(max = 50)\n  List&lt;@Valid OrderItem&gt; items,\n\n  @Future\n  LocalDate deliveryDate\n) {}</pre><br><strong>Step 2 — trigger validation in controller:</strong><br><pre>@PostMapping(\"/orders\")\nResponseEntity&lt;?&gt; create(@Valid @RequestBody CreateOrderRequest req) { ... }</pre><br><strong>Step 3 — handle failures:</strong> Spring throws <code>MethodArgumentNotValidException</code> when validation fails — handle in <code>@RestControllerAdvice</code>.<br><br><strong>Validation groups:</strong> use <code>@Validated(OnCreate.class)</code> to apply different constraints per operation (create vs update)."},

    {q:"What is Spring WebFlux and when should you choose it over MVC?",d:"hard",id:"spring-webflux-should-you",
     a:"Spring WebFlux is a <em>reactive, non-blocking</em> web framework. It runs on Netty (by default) using an event-loop model — a small number of threads handle thousands of concurrent connections via non-blocking I/O.<br><br><strong>Core types:</strong> <code>Mono&lt;T&gt;</code> (0 or 1 item) and <code>Flux&lt;T&gt;</code> (0..N items) from Project Reactor.<br><br><strong>Choose WebFlux when:</strong><ul><li>Integrating with reactive data stores (R2DBC, Reactive MongoDB, Cassandra)</li><li>Building streaming APIs (Server-Sent Events, WebSocket)</li><li>Very high concurrency with many slow I/O operations</li><li>Entire stack is reactive (no blocking calls)</li></ul><br><strong>Choose Spring MVC when:</strong><ul><li>Team is unfamiliar with reactive programming</li><li>Using JDBC/JPA (inherently blocking)</li><li>Simpler debugging and stack traces are preferred</li></ul><br><strong>Java 21 + Virtual Threads</strong> close the throughput gap for blocking I/O — MVC with virtual threads competes with WebFlux for most workloads.<br><br><strong>Example — reactive controller with R2DBC repository:</strong><br><pre>@RestController\n@RequestMapping(\"/products\")\npublic class ProductController {\n\n  private final ProductRepository repo; // extends ReactiveCrudRepository\n\n  @GetMapping(produces = MediaType.TEXT_EVENT_STREAM_VALUE)\n  public Flux&lt;Product&gt; streamAll() {\n    return repo.findAll();              // non-blocking, streams rows as they arrive\n  }\n\n  @GetMapping(\"/{id}\")\n  public Mono&lt;ResponseEntity&lt;Product&gt;&gt; getById(@PathVariable Long id) {\n    return repo.findById(id)\n      .map(ResponseEntity::ok)\n      .defaultIfEmpty(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());\n  }\n}</pre>"},

    {q:"What is Spring Data and what is query derivation?",d:"medium",id:"spring-data-query-derivation",
     a:"Spring Data provides repository abstractions across many data stores. Core interfaces: <code>CrudRepository</code>, <code>PagingAndSortingRepository</code>, <code>JpaRepository</code>.<br><br><strong>Query derivation:</strong> Spring Data parses the method name and generates the query automatically:<br><pre>List&lt;User&gt; findByEmailAndActiveTrueOrderByCreatedAtDesc(String email);\n// → SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ? AND active = true ORDER BY created_at DESC\n\nOptional&lt;User&gt; findFirstByPhoneOrderByCreatedAtDesc(String phone);</pre><br><strong>@Query</strong> for custom JPQL or native SQL:<br><pre>@Query(\"SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.email = :email\")\nOptional&lt;User&gt; findByEmailCustom(@Param(\"email\") String email);\n\n@Query(value = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = :email\", nativeQuery = true)\nOptional&lt;User&gt; findByEmailNative(@Param(\"email\") String email);</pre><br><strong>Projections:</strong> return interface projections (<code>interface UserSummary { String getName(); }</code>) or DTO projections to avoid over-fetching entire entities."},

    {q:"What is Spring Retry and how do you combine it with circuit breaker?",d:"medium",id:"spring-retry-you-combine",
     a:"<strong>Spring Retry</strong> provides declarative retry support:<br><pre>@EnableRetry  // on @Configuration class\n\n@Retryable(\n  retryFor = {HttpServerErrorException.class, ResourceAccessException.class},\n  maxAttempts = 3,\n  backoff = @Backoff(delay = 500, multiplier = 2, random = true)\n)\npublic Order fetchOrder(String id) { ... }\n\n@Recover\npublic Order fallback(HttpServerErrorException ex, String id) {\n  return Order.empty();\n}</pre><br><strong>With Resilience4j Circuit Breaker</strong> (more production-grade):<br><pre>@CircuitBreaker(name = \"orderService\", fallbackMethod = \"fallback\")\n@Retry(name = \"orderService\")\npublic Order fetchOrder(String id) { ... }</pre><br><strong>Strategy:</strong> Retry handles transient failures; Circuit Breaker handles persistent failures. Order matters — typically Retry wraps the operation, Circuit Breaker wraps Retry. Configure failure rate thresholds, wait durations, and permitted calls in half-open state via <code>application.yml</code>."},

    {q:"How does Spring Boot handle externalized configuration priority?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-handle-externalized",
     a:"Spring Boot applies configuration sources in this priority order (later = higher priority, overrides earlier):<ol><li>Default properties (<code>SpringApplication.setDefaultProperties()</code>)</li><li><code>@PropertySource</code> annotations on <code>@Configuration</code> classes</li><li><code>application.properties</code> / <code>application.yml</code> (inside JAR)</li><li>Profile-specific files: <code>application-{profile}.yml</code></li><li><code>application.properties</code> / <code>application.yml</code> outside the JAR (same dir)</li><li>OS environment variables</li><li>JVM system properties: <code>-Dkey=value</code></li><li>Command-line args: <code>--key=value</code></li></ol><br><strong>Config Server</strong> properties are fetched during bootstrap (before context starts) and sit between steps 4 and 5 in practice.<br><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> prefer <code>@ConfigurationProperties</code> over <code>@Value</code> — type-safe, validated, IDE-autocompleted, and bindable to nested objects.<br><br><strong>Example — override chain in action:</strong><br><pre># application.yml (priority 3 — inside JAR)\nserver:\n  port: 8080\napp:\n  timeout: 30s\n\n# application-prod.yml (priority 4 — profile-specific, overrides above)\nserver:\n  port: 8443\n\n# Command-line arg wins everything (priority 8)\njava -jar app.jar --server.port=9090\n# Effective port: 9090</pre>"},

    {q:"What is the Spring Boot Actuator /health endpoint and how do you customise it?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-actuator-health",
     a:"<code>/actuator/health</code> aggregates the health of all registered <code>HealthIndicator</code> beans. Returns 200 with <code>{\"status\":\"UP\"}</code> or 503 with <code>DOWN</code>.<br><br><strong>Built-in indicators:</strong> DataSource (DB ping), Redis (PING), Kafka (describe topics), Disk space, Mail.<br><br><strong>Custom health indicator:</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class ExternalApiHealthIndicator implements HealthIndicator {\n  @Override\n  public Health health() {\n    try {\n      externalApi.ping();\n      return Health.up().withDetail(\"api\", \"reachable\").build();\n    } catch (Exception e) {\n      return Health.down().withDetail(\"error\", e.getMessage()).build();\n    }\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Kubernetes probes</strong> — separate endpoints:<ul><li>Liveness: <code>/actuator/health/liveness</code> — is the app alive? (restart if DOWN)</li><li>Readiness: <code>/actuator/health/readiness</code> — is the app ready for traffic?</li></ul>Config: <code>management.health.probes.enabled=true</code>"},

    {q:"What is a Spring Boot Starter and how would you create a custom one?",d:"hard",id:"spring-boot-starter-would",
     a:"A Starter is a Maven/Gradle dependency that bundles all required dependencies and auto-configuration for a specific feature. Example: <code>spring-boot-starter-web</code> pulls in Tomcat, Spring MVC, Jackson, and validation.<br><br><strong>Creating a custom starter (e.g., for an internal audit library):</strong><ol><li>Create <code>audit-spring-boot-autoconfigure</code> module with the auto-configuration class:<br><pre>@AutoConfiguration\n@ConditionalOnClass(AuditService.class)\n@EnableConfigurationProperties(AuditProperties.class)\npublic class AuditAutoConfiguration {\n  @Bean @ConditionalOnMissingBean\n  AuditService auditService(AuditProperties props) {\n    return new AuditService(props.getEndpoint());\n  }\n}</pre></li><li>Register in <code>META-INF/spring/org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.AutoConfiguration.imports</code></li><li>Create <code>audit-spring-boot-starter</code> POM that depends on the autoconfigure module</li><li>Consumers add only the starter — auto-configuration activates when <code>AuditService</code> is on the classpath</li></ol>"}
  ]
};

SEC_SPRING.qs.push(
  {q:"What is Spring's @Transactional rollback behaviour and how do you customise it?",d:"hard",id:"spring-s-transactional-rollback",
     a:"By default, <code>@Transactional</code> rolls back only on <strong>unchecked exceptions</strong> (RuntimeException and Error). Checked exceptions do NOT trigger a rollback — the transaction commits even if you catch and rethrow a checked exception.<br><br><strong>Customise rollback rules:</strong><br><pre>// Roll back on ALL exceptions including checked\n@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)\n\n// Roll back only on specific exception\n@Transactional(rollbackFor = InsufficientFundsException.class)\n\n// Do NOT roll back on a specific unchecked exception\n@Transactional(noRollbackFor = OptimisticLockException.class)</pre><br><strong>Programmatic rollback:</strong><br><pre>@Transactional\npublic void process() {\n  try { risky(); }\n  catch (BusinessException e) {\n    TransactionAspectSupport.currentTransactionStatus().setRollbackOnly();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Testing:</strong> add <code>@Transactional</code> to test methods — Spring rolls back after each test, leaving the DB clean."},

  {q:"What is the difference between FetchType.LAZY and FetchType.EAGER and which should you default to?",d:"medium",id:"fetchtype-lazy-fetchtype-eager",
     a:"<strong>FetchType.LAZY (default for @OneToMany, @ManyToMany):</strong> the association is loaded only when first accessed in Java code. Hibernate generates a SELECT only when <code>order.getItems()</code> is called.<br><br><strong>FetchType.EAGER (default for @ManyToOne, @OneToOne):</strong> the association is always loaded immediately when the parent entity is loaded — even if you never access it.<br><br><strong>Why EAGER is dangerous:</strong><ul><li>Loads data you might not need (wasted DB work and memory)</li><li>Can silently cause N+1 queries (EAGER on collections is especially bad)</li><li>Cannot be overridden per-query — always loads</li></ul><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> default everything to LAZY. Load associations explicitly when needed using JOIN FETCH, @EntityGraph, or DTO projections:<br><pre>// @ManyToOne defaults to EAGER — override it:\n@ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)\nprivate Customer customer;</pre>"},

  {q:"How does Spring Boot handle graceful shutdown?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-handle-graceful",
     a:"When Kubernetes sends SIGTERM to terminate a pod, Spring Boot needs to finish in-flight requests before shutting down — or you'll get 500s for users mid-request.<br><br><strong>Enable graceful shutdown:</strong><br><pre>server.shutdown=graceful\nspring.lifecycle.timeout-per-shutdown-phase=30s</pre><br><strong>What happens:</strong><ol><li>SIGTERM received</li><li>Readiness probe returns DOWN — load balancer stops sending new traffic</li><li>Spring waits up to 30s for in-flight requests to complete</li><li>Executor services drain (Kafka consumers, async tasks)</li><li>Beans destroyed in reverse creation order</li><li>JVM exits</li></ol><br><strong>With Kubernetes:</strong> set <code>terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 60</code> in your pod spec — larger than Spring's timeout to give it enough time.<br><br><strong>@PreDestroy and DisposableBean:</strong> run cleanup logic (close connections, flush caches) when the context is destroyed — guaranteed to run before JVM exit."},

  {q:"What is the difference between @PathVariable, @RequestParam, and @RequestBody?",d:"easy",id:"pathvariable-requestparam-requestbody",
     a:"<strong>@PathVariable:</strong> extracts values from the URI path template.<br><pre>@GetMapping(\"/orders/{id}\")\nOrder get(@PathVariable String id) { ... }\n// GET /orders/abc-123 → id = \"abc-123\"</pre><br><strong>@RequestParam:</strong> extracts values from query string or form data.<br><pre>@GetMapping(\"/orders\")\nPage&lt;Order&gt; list(\n  @RequestParam(defaultValue = \"0\") int page,\n  @RequestParam(required = false) String status\n) { ... }\n// GET /orders?page=2&status=PENDING</pre><br><strong>@RequestBody:</strong> deserialises the HTTP request body (JSON/XML) into a Java object via Jackson.<br><pre>@PostMapping(\"/orders\")\nResponseEntity&lt;Order&gt; create(@Valid @RequestBody CreateOrderRequest req) { ... }\n// POST /orders with JSON body</pre><br><strong>@RequestHeader:</strong> extracts individual headers: <code>@RequestHeader(\"X-Correlation-Id\") String correlationId</code><br><strong>@CookieValue:</strong> extracts cookies: <code>@CookieValue(\"sessionId\") String sessionId</code>"},

  {q:"How do you implement an idempotent REST endpoint in Spring Boot?",d:"hard",id:"you-implement-idempotent-rest",
     a:"Idempotency is critical for payment, order creation, and any operation where client retries could cause duplicates.<br><br><strong>Pattern:</strong> client sends a unique <code>Idempotency-Key</code> header. Server checks if this key was already processed:<br><pre>@PostMapping(\"/payments\")\nResponseEntity&lt;Payment&gt; charge(\n  @RequestHeader(\"Idempotency-Key\") String key,\n  @RequestBody @Valid ChargeRequest req\n) {\n  // Check if already processed\n  Optional&lt;Payment&gt; existing = idempotencyStore.find(key);\n  if (existing.isPresent()) {\n    return ResponseEntity.ok(existing.get()); // replay stored result\n  }\n\n  // Process\n  Payment payment = paymentService.charge(req);\n\n  // Store result linked to key (TTL: 24h)\n  idempotencyStore.save(key, payment, Duration.ofHours(24));\n  return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(payment);\n}</pre><br><strong>Storage:</strong> Redis with TTL — <code>SETNX payment:key:{uuid} {result}</code><br><br><strong>Concurrency:</strong> use Redis distributed lock to prevent two concurrent requests with the same key both processing simultaneously."}
);

SEC_SPRING.qs.push(
  {q:"How does @Scheduled work and what are its pitfalls in production?",d:"medium",id:"scheduled-work-its-pitfalls",
     a:"<code>@Scheduled</code> runs methods on a fixed schedule. Enable with <code>@EnableScheduling</code> on a config class.<br><br><strong>Scheduling options:</strong><br><pre>@Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)           // every 5s from start of previous execution\n@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 5000)          // 5s AFTER previous execution finishes\n@Scheduled(initialDelay = 1000, fixedRate = 5000)\n@Scheduled(cron = \"0 0 9 * * MON-FRI\") // 9am weekdays\n@Scheduled(cron = \"@daily\")            // shorthand\n\n// Externalise the schedule:\n@Scheduled(cron = \"${reports.cron:0 0 2 * * *}\")\nvoid report() { ... }</pre><br><strong>Cron format:</strong> <code>second minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week</code><br><br><strong>Critical pitfalls:</strong><ul><li><strong>Single-threaded by default:</strong> all @Scheduled tasks share ONE thread. A slow task blocks all others.</li><li><strong>Multiple instances:</strong> in a clustered deployment, every instance runs the schedule — use ShedLock or Quartz clustered scheduler to ensure only one instance runs per execution</li><li><strong>Self-invocation:</strong> calling another @Transactional method from the same bean bypasses the proxy</li></ul><br><strong>Fix — configure a thread-pool TaskScheduler:</strong><br><pre>@Bean\nTaskScheduler taskScheduler() {\n  ThreadPoolTaskScheduler s = new ThreadPoolTaskScheduler();\n  s.setPoolSize(5);\n  s.setThreadNamePrefix(\"scheduler-\");\n  return s;\n}</pre>"},

  {q:"What is the difference between @EventListener and @TransactionalEventListener?",d:"hard",id:"eventlistener-transactionaleventlistener",
     a:"<strong>@EventListener:</strong> fires immediately when <code>ApplicationEventPublisher.publishEvent()</code> is called — synchronously, in the same thread, <em>within the same transaction</em> as the publisher.<br><pre>@EventListener\npublic void onOrderPlaced(OrderPlacedEvent event) {\n  // Fires BEFORE the publishing transaction commits\n  // If this throws, the publisher's transaction rolls back too!\n  emailService.send(event.getEmail());\n}</pre><br><strong>@TransactionalEventListener:</strong> defers execution until after the publishing transaction commits — guaranteeing the data is actually persisted before the listener runs.<br><pre>@TransactionalEventListener(phase = TransactionPhase.AFTER_COMMIT)\npublic void onOrderPlaced(OrderPlacedEvent event) {\n  // Fires ONLY after order is committed to DB\n  // Email failure does NOT roll back the order transaction\n  emailService.send(event.getEmail());\n}</pre><br><strong>Phases:</strong><ul><li><code>AFTER_COMMIT</code> (default) — after successful commit</li><li><code>AFTER_ROLLBACK</code> — after rollback (for compensation/alerting)</li><li><code>AFTER_COMPLETION</code> — after commit or rollback</li><li><code>BEFORE_COMMIT</code> — just before commit</li></ul><br><strong>When to use which:</strong> use <code>@TransactionalEventListener</code> whenever the listener reads the DB or calls an external system — guarantees consistency. Use <code>@EventListener</code> only for in-memory operations that don't depend on committed state.<br><br><strong>Note:</strong> if no active transaction exists, the event is dropped by default. Set <code>fallbackExecution = true</code> to fire even without a transaction."},

  {q:"What is the difference between a Servlet Filter and a Spring Interceptor?",d:"medium",id:"servlet-filter-spring-interceptor",
     a:"Both intercept HTTP requests but at different layers of the stack:<br><br><strong>Filter (javax.servlet.Filter / jakarta.servlet.Filter):</strong><ul><li>Part of the Servlet spec — runs before Spring's DispatcherServlet</li><li>Sees raw <code>HttpServletRequest</code>/<code>HttpServletResponse</code></li><li>Can intercept ALL requests including static resources and non-Spring endpoints</li><li>Best for: authentication/JWT extraction, CORS, compression, rate limiting, request logging</li></ul><br><pre>@Component\npublic class CorrelationIdFilter implements Filter {\n  public void doFilter(ServletRequest req, ServletResponse res, FilterChain chain)\n      throws IOException, ServletException {\n    MDC.put(\"correlationId\", ((HttpServletRequest)req).getHeader(\"X-Correlation-ID\"));\n    chain.doFilter(req, res);\n    MDC.clear();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Spring Interceptor (HandlerInterceptor):</strong><ul><li>Part of Spring MVC — runs inside DispatcherServlet after controller mapping is resolved</li><li>Has access to the handler method and ModelAndView</li><li>Three hook points: <code>preHandle()</code> (return false to abort), <code>postHandle()</code>, <code>afterCompletion()</code></li><li>Has full access to Spring context and beans</li><li>Best for: auth/role checks, performance logging, audit trail per controller action</li></ul><br><strong>Order of execution:</strong> Filter → DispatcherServlet → Interceptor → Controller"},

  {q:"What are @Conditional annotations and how do you create a custom one?",d:"hard",id:"conditional-annotations-you-create",
     a:"Conditional annotations control whether a bean or configuration is registered based on a condition evaluated at startup. Spring Boot's entire auto-configuration relies on these.<br><br><strong>Built-in Spring Boot conditionals:</strong><br><pre>@ConditionalOnClass(RedisTemplate.class)      // class on classpath?\n@ConditionalOnMissingBean(CacheManager.class) // no existing bean?\n@ConditionalOnProperty(\n  name = \"feature.notifications\",\n  havingValue = \"true\",\n  matchIfMissing = false\n)\n@ConditionalOnExpression(\"${feature.x} && ${feature.y}\")\n@ConditionalOnWebApplication\n@ConditionalOnCloudPlatform(CloudPlatform.KUBERNETES)</pre><br><strong>Custom condition:</strong><br><pre>public class OnWeekdayCondition implements Condition {\n  @Override\n  public boolean matches(ConditionContext ctx, AnnotatedTypeMetadata meta) {\n    DayOfWeek day = LocalDate.now().getDayOfWeek();\n    return day != SATURDAY && day != SUNDAY;\n  }\n}\n\n// Create a meta-annotation for clean usage:\n@Target({TYPE, METHOD})\n@Retention(RUNTIME)\n@Conditional(OnWeekdayCondition.class)\npublic @interface ConditionalOnWeekday {}\n\n@Bean @ConditionalOnWeekday\nJobRunner weekdayJobRunner() { return new JobRunner(); }</pre>"},

  {q:"What is Spring Boot's RestClient and how does it differ from RestTemplate and WebClient?",d:"medium",id:"spring-boot-s-restclient",
     a:"<strong>RestTemplate</strong> (Spring 3+): synchronous, blocking HTTP client. Callback-heavy API. In maintenance mode — no new features. Still works in existing code.<br><br><strong>WebClient</strong> (Spring 5+): reactive, non-blocking. Returns <code>Mono/Flux</code>. Powerful but forces reactive programming on callers.<br><br><strong>RestClient</strong> (Spring 6.1 / Boot 3.2): modern synchronous fluent API — the replacement for RestTemplate without requiring reactive types:<br><pre>RestClient client = RestClient.builder()\n  .baseUrl(\"https://api.example.com\")\n  .defaultHeader(\"Authorization\", \"Bearer \" + token)\n  .build();\n\n// GET\nOrder order = client.get()\n  .uri(\"/orders/{id}\", orderId)\n  .retrieve()\n  .onStatus(HttpStatusCode::is4xxClientError,\n    (req, res) -&gt; { throw new OrderNotFoundException(orderId); })\n  .body(Order.class);\n\n// POST\nclient.post()\n  .uri(\"/orders\")\n  .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)\n  .body(createRequest)\n  .retrieve()\n  .toBodilessEntity();</pre><br><strong>Decision guide:</strong> RestClient for new synchronous code; WebClient for reactive code; OpenFeign for declarative microservice clients. Migrate RestTemplate to RestClient gradually."},

  {q:"How do you implement MDC-based correlation ID logging in Spring Boot?",d:"medium",id:"you-implement-mdc-based",
     a:"MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context) attaches key-value pairs to the current thread's log context — every log line in that request automatically includes them without passing parameters through every method.<br><br><strong>Step 1 — Filter to set MDC:</strong><br><pre>@Component @Order(1)\npublic class CorrelationFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {\n  @Override\n  protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest req,\n      HttpServletResponse res, FilterChain chain)\n      throws ServletException, IOException {\n    String id = Optional.ofNullable(req.getHeader(\"X-Correlation-Id\"))\n      .orElse(UUID.randomUUID().toString());\n    MDC.put(\"correlationId\", id);\n    MDC.put(\"userId\", extractUserId(req));\n    MDC.put(\"path\", req.getRequestURI());\n    res.setHeader(\"X-Correlation-Id\", id);\n    try {\n      chain.doFilter(req, res);\n    } finally {\n      MDC.clear(); // MUST clear — thread pool reuse!\n    }\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Step 2 — logback pattern:</strong><br><pre>&lt;pattern&gt;%d [%X{correlationId}] [%X{userId}] %-5level %logger - %msg%n&lt;/pattern&gt;</pre><br><strong>Step 3 — propagate to async threads</strong> using <code>TaskDecorator</code>:<br><pre>executor.setTaskDecorator(runnable -> {\n  Map&lt;String,String&gt; ctx = MDC.getCopyOfContextMap();\n  return () -> { MDC.setContextMap(ctx); runnable.run(); MDC.clear(); };\n});</pre><br><strong>JSON structured logging</strong> — add LogstashEncoder to log MDC as JSON fields (searchable in Kibana/Datadog):<br><pre>&lt;appender name=\"JSON\"&gt;\n  &lt;encoder class=\"net.logstash.logback.encoder.LogstashEncoder\"/&gt;\n&lt;/appender&gt;</pre><br>With Micrometer Tracing, <code>traceId</code> and <code>spanId</code> are automatically added to MDC."},

  {q:"What is Spring Batch and when would you use it?",d:"hard",id:"spring-batch-would-you",
     a:"Spring Batch provides a framework for processing large volumes of data in chunks — reading, processing, and writing with restart/retry/skip capabilities.<br><br><strong>Core concepts:</strong><ul><li><strong>Job:</strong> the overall batch process, composed of Steps</li><li><strong>Step:</strong> one phase of work — Tasklet (single operation) or Chunk-oriented (read-process-write)</li><li><strong>ItemReader:</strong> reads data (JdbcCursorItemReader, FlatFileItemReader, JpaPagingItemReader)</li><li><strong>ItemProcessor:</strong> transforms/validates each item (optional)</li><li><strong>ItemWriter:</strong> writes results (JdbcBatchItemWriter, JpaItemWriter)</li></ul><br><pre>@Bean\nJob importJob(JobRepository repo, Step importStep) {\n  return new JobBuilder(\"importUsers\", repo)\n    .start(importStep)\n    .build();\n}\n\n@Bean\nStep importStep(JobRepository repo, PlatformTransactionManager tx) {\n  return new StepBuilder(\"importStep\", repo)\n    .&lt;UserCsv, User&gt;chunk(100, tx) // process 100 items per transaction\n    .reader(csvReader())\n    .processor(userProcessor())\n    .writer(dbWriter())\n    .faultTolerant()\n    .skip(ValidationException.class).skipLimit(10)\n    .retry(DeadlockException.class).retryLimit(3)\n    .build();\n}</pre><br><strong>Production features:</strong> restart from last checkpoint on failure (no reprocessing), skip/retry policies, parallel steps, partitioned processing for large datasets, full job history stored in DB.<br><br><strong>Use Spring Batch for:</strong> ETL pipelines, month-end reports, bulk data migration, invoice processing — any batch operation over millions of records."},

  {q:"How do you create a custom Spring Boot Actuator endpoint?",d:"hard",id:"you-create-custom-spring",
     a:"Register a custom endpoint at <code>/actuator/{id}</code> using the <code>@Endpoint</code> annotation:<br><br><pre>@Component\n@Endpoint(id = \"featureFlags\")\npublic class FeatureFlagEndpoint {\n\n  private final FeatureFlagService svc;\n\n  @ReadOperation  // HTTP GET /actuator/featureFlags\n  public Map&lt;String, Boolean&gt; flags() {\n    return svc.getAllFlags();\n  }\n\n  @ReadOperation  // HTTP GET /actuator/featureFlags/{name}\n  public Boolean flag(@Selector String name) {\n    return svc.isEnabled(name);\n  }\n\n  @WriteOperation // HTTP POST /actuator/featureFlags/{name}\n  public void toggle(@Selector String name, boolean enabled) {\n    svc.setEnabled(name, enabled);\n  }\n\n  @DeleteOperation // HTTP DELETE /actuator/featureFlags/{name}\n  public void remove(@Selector String name) {\n    svc.remove(name);\n  }\n}</pre><br>Expose it: <code>management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=featureFlags</code><br><br><code>@WebEndpoint</code> — HTTP only. <code>@JmxEndpoint</code> — JMX only. <code>@Endpoint</code> — both.<br><br>Useful for: feature toggles, cache management, triggering maintenance tasks, exposing internal state for ops teams."},

  {q:"What is @ConfigurationProperties and why prefer it over @Value?",d:"medium",id:"configurationproperties-prefer-it-over",
     a:"<strong>@Value:</strong> injects a single property — simple but limited:<br><pre>@Value(\"${mail.host}\") private String host;\n@Value(\"${mail.port:587}\") private int port;</pre><br><strong>Problems at scale:</strong> scattered across classes, no type safety, no validation, no IDE auto-complete.<br><br><strong>@ConfigurationProperties:</strong> binds an entire prefix to a typed POJO — validated, IDE-supported, supports Java records:<br><pre>@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = \"app.payment\")\n@Validated\npublic record PaymentProperties(\n  @NotBlank String apiKey,\n  @NotNull URL endpoint,\n  @Min(1) @Max(10) int maxRetries,\n  Duration timeout  // auto-converts \"30s\" → Duration.ofSeconds(30)\n) {}</pre><br>Register: <code>@EnableConfigurationProperties(PaymentProperties.class)</code> or <code>@Component</code>.<br><br><strong>application.yml:</strong><br><pre>app.payment:\n  api-key: sk-...\n  endpoint: https://pay.example.com\n  max-retries: 3\n  timeout: 30s</pre><br><strong>Advantages over @Value:</strong><ul><li>Type conversion: String → Duration, URL, DataSize, enums</li><li>JSR-303 validation on startup — fail fast with a clear error</li><li>IDE autocompletion via the metadata processor</li><li>Nested objects and lists bind naturally</li><li>Relaxed binding: <code>max-retries</code>, <code>MAX_RETRIES</code>, <code>maxRetries</code> all work</li></ul>"},

  {q:"What is Spring's ApplicationContext and how does it differ from BeanFactory?",d:"medium",id:"spring-s-applicationcontext-it",
     a:"<strong>BeanFactory</strong>: the root IoC container interface. Provides bean instantiation, dependency injection, and lifecycle management. Lazy by default — beans created on first request. Minimal footprint.<br><br><strong>ApplicationContext</strong>: extends BeanFactory with enterprise features:<ul><li><strong>Eager initialisation</strong> — all singleton beans created at startup (catches wiring errors early)</li><li><strong>Event publishing</strong> via <code>ApplicationEventPublisher</code></li><li><strong>Internationalisation</strong> via <code>MessageSource</code></li><li><strong>Resource loading</strong> (<code>classpath:</code>, <code>file:</code>, <code>http:</code>)</li><li><strong>Environment and profiles</strong> abstraction</li><li><strong>AOP auto-proxy creation</strong></li><li><strong>@Scheduled, @Async, @Transactional</strong> support</li></ul><br><strong>Implementations:</strong><ul><li><code>AnnotationConfigApplicationContext</code> — standalone Java config</li><li><code>AnnotationConfigServletWebServerApplicationContext</code> — Spring Boot web app</li><li><code>GenericWebApplicationContext</code> — test slices</li></ul><br>In practice, always use <code>ApplicationContext</code>. BeanFactory is only relevant in memory-constrained embedded environments.<br><br><strong>Example — ApplicationContext (eager) vs BeanFactory (lazy):</strong><br><pre>// ApplicationContext — all singletons created at startup (standard)\nApplicationContext ctx =\n  new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext(AppConfig.class);\n// All beans already constructed here — wiring errors caught immediately\nOrderService svc = ctx.getBean(OrderService.class);\n\n// BeanFactory — lazy, rarely used directly outside frameworks\nDefaultListableBeanFactory bf = new DefaultListableBeanFactory();\nnew XmlBeanDefinitionReader(bf).loadBeanDefinitions(\"beans.xml\");\n// Beans NOT created yet — only instantiated on first getBean() call\nOrderService svc2 = (OrderService) bf.getBean(\"orderService\");</pre>"},

  {q:"How does Spring Boot handle circular dependencies and how do you break them?",d:"hard",id:"spring-boot-handle-circular",
     a:"A circular dependency occurs when Bean A depends on Bean B and Bean B depends on Bean A. Spring Boot 2.6+ throws <code>BeanCurrentlyInCreationException</code> at startup by default — this is intentional.<br><br><strong>Spring's handling by injection type:</strong><ul><li><strong>Constructor injection (recommended):</strong> Spring CANNOT resolve — throws at startup. Forces you to fix the design.</li><li><strong>Setter/field injection:</strong> Spring CAN resolve by creating a partially-initialised proxy — but this is fragile and hides the design problem.</li></ul><br><strong>Proper fixes (in order of preference):</strong><br><br><strong>1. Refactor — extract a third bean:</strong> A and B depending on each other usually means there's a missing abstraction. Extract the shared logic into Bean C that both depend on.<br><br><strong>2. Event-driven:</strong> instead of A calling B directly, A publishes an event and B listens — fully decouples them.<br><br><strong>3. @Lazy on one constructor parameter:</strong><br><pre>public ServiceA(@Lazy ServiceB b) { this.b = b; }</pre>Spring injects a proxy resolved on first use. Avoids the circular dep but hides the design smell.<br><br><strong>4. ApplicationContext lookup (last resort):</strong><br><pre>@Autowired ApplicationContext ctx;\nServiceB b = ctx.getBean(ServiceB.class);</pre><br><strong>Allow globally (not recommended):</strong> <code>spring.main.allow-circular-references=true</code><br><br><strong>Root cause:</strong> circular dependencies almost always indicate a design problem — usually a violation of the Single Responsibility Principle."},

  {q:"How do you implement a custom Spring Boot HealthIndicator and InfoContributor?",d:"medium",id:"you-implement-custom-spring",
     a:"<strong>Custom HealthIndicator:</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class ThirdPartyApiHealthIndicator implements HealthIndicator {\n\n  private final PaymentGatewayClient client;\n\n  @Override\n  public Health health() {\n    try {\n      PingResponse resp = client.ping();\n      if (resp.isOk()) {\n        return Health.up()\n          .withDetail(\"latency_ms\", resp.getLatency())\n          .withDetail(\"region\", resp.getRegion())\n          .build();\n      }\n      return Health.down().withDetail(\"reason\", resp.getError()).build();\n    } catch (Exception e) {\n      return Health.down(e).build();\n    }\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Custom InfoContributor</strong> (adds data to <code>/actuator/info</code>):<br><pre>@Component\npublic class AppInfoContributor implements InfoContributor {\n  @Override\n  public void contribute(Info.Builder builder) {\n    builder.withDetail(\"feature-flags\", Map.of(\n      \"newCheckout\", featureFlags.isEnabled(\"new-checkout\"),\n      \"darkMode\", featureFlags.isEnabled(\"dark-mode\")\n    ));\n  }\n}</pre><br>Expose info endpoint: <code>management.info.env.enabled=true</code>, <code>management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health,info</code>"},

  {q:"How do you configure multiple DataSources in Spring Boot?",d:"hard",id:"you-configure-multiple-datasources",
     a:"When your application needs to connect to two databases (e.g., primary PostgreSQL + reporting MySQL):<br><br><strong>Step 1 — properties:</strong><br><pre>primary.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://...\nprimary.datasource.username=user1\nreporting.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://...\nreporting.datasource.username=user2</pre><br><strong>Step 2 — config class per datasource:</strong><br><pre>@Configuration\n@EnableJpaRepositories(\n  basePackages = \"com.app.primary\",\n  entityManagerFactoryRef = \"primaryEntityManagerFactory\",\n  transactionManagerRef = \"primaryTransactionManager\"\n)\npublic class PrimaryDataSourceConfig {\n\n  @Primary @Bean\n  @ConfigurationProperties(\"primary.datasource\")\n  DataSource primaryDataSource() { return DataSourceBuilder.create().build(); }\n\n  @Primary @Bean\n  LocalContainerEntityManagerFactoryBean primaryEntityManagerFactory(\n      DataSource ds, JpaProperties props) { ... }\n\n  @Primary @Bean\n  PlatformTransactionManager primaryTransactionManager(\n      EntityManagerFactory emf) { return new JpaTransactionManager(emf); }\n}</pre><br><strong>Key rules:</strong> mark one DataSource as <code>@Primary</code>. Place entity classes and repositories in separate packages per datasource. Each datasource needs its own EntityManagerFactory and TransactionManager."},

  {q:"How does Spring Boot 3 differ from Spring Boot 2 — key breaking changes?",d:"hard",id:"spring-boot-3-differ",
     a:"<strong>Major breaking changes in Spring Boot 3:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Java 17+ baseline:</strong> Java 8/11 apps must upgrade to Java 17 minimum. Java 21 (latest LTS) recommended.<br><br><strong>2. Jakarta EE namespace migration:</strong> <code>javax.*</code> packages renamed to <code>jakarta.*</code><br><pre>import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;  // Spring Boot 2\nimport jakarta.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest; // Spring Boot 3</pre>Affects: Servlet, JPA, Bean Validation, JMS, Mail, etc. All libraries must be Jakarta-compatible.<br><br><strong>3. Spring Framework 6:</strong> requires Hibernate 6, Tomcat 10, etc.<br><br><strong>4. Native image support (GraalVM):</strong> AOT compilation replaces runtime reflection — drastically faster startup and lower memory.<br><br><strong>5. Observability enhancements:</strong> Micrometer Observation API is the unified abstraction for metrics/traces/logs.<br><br><strong>6. Spring Security 6:</strong><ul><li><code>WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter</code> removed — use <code>@Bean SecurityFilterChain</code></li><li>Lambda DSL is now the standard</li></ul><br><strong>Migration tip:</strong> use <code>spring-boot-properties-migrator</code> to detect deprecated properties. Test thoroughly — many third-party libraries lagged Jakarta EE support."},

  {q:"What is @Lookup and when do you need a prototype bean inside a singleton?",d:"hard",id:"lookup-you-need-prototype",
     a:"<strong>Problem:</strong> singleton beans are created once at startup. If a singleton depends on a prototype bean, the prototype is injected once and reused — defeating prototype scope.<br><br><strong>Method injection with @Lookup:</strong> Spring generates a subclass that overrides the @Lookup method to return a fresh prototype instance each call.<br><pre>@Component\n@Scope(\"prototype\")\npublic class OrderProcessor { ... }\n\n@Component\npublic class OrderService {\n  public void process(Order order) {\n    OrderProcessor processor = getProcessor(); // new instance each call\n    processor.process(order);\n  }\n\n  @Lookup\n  protected OrderProcessor getProcessor() {\n    return null; // Spring overrides this\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Alternative — ObjectProvider (modern, type-safe):</strong><br><pre>@Autowired ObjectProvider&lt;OrderProcessor&gt; processorProvider;\n\npublic void process(Order order) {\n  OrderProcessor processor = processorProvider.getObject(); // new instance\n  processor.process(order);\n}</pre><br><strong>Alternative — ApplicationContext.getBean():</strong><br><pre>@Autowired ApplicationContext ctx;\nOrderProcessor p = ctx.getBean(OrderProcessor.class);</pre>"},

  {q:"How does Spring Security method-level security work (@PreAuthorize, @PostAuthorize)?",d:"hard",id:"spring-security-method-level",
     a:"Method-level security lets you protect service methods with SpEL expressions — finer-grained control than URL-based security.<br><br><strong>Enable:</strong><br><pre>@Configuration\n@EnableMethodSecurity(prePostEnabled = true)\npublic class SecurityConfig { }</pre><br><strong>@PreAuthorize — check before method executes:</strong><br><pre>@PreAuthorize(\"hasRole('ADMIN')\")\npublic void deleteUser(Long id) { ... }\n\n@PreAuthorize(\"#userId == authentication.principal.id or hasRole('ADMIN')\")\npublic Order getOrder(Long orderId, Long userId) { ... }</pre><br><strong>@PostAuthorize — check after method returns (access to return value):</strong><br><pre>@PostAuthorize(\"returnObject.owner == authentication.name\")\npublic Order getOrder(Long id) { ... }\n// Method executes, but if owner doesn't match, throws AccessDeniedException</pre><br><strong>@PreFilter / @PostFilter — filter collections:</strong><br><pre>@PreFilter(\"filterObject.active == true\")\npublic void processOrders(List&lt;Order&gt; orders) { ... }\n// Spring removes inactive orders from the list before method sees it</pre><br><strong>SpEL expressions:</strong> <code>hasRole('X')</code>, <code>hasAuthority('X')</code>, <code>isAuthenticated()</code>, <code>authentication.principal.id</code>, <code>#methodParam</code>, <code>returnObject.field</code>."},

  {q:"How do you handle multipart file uploads in Spring Boot?",d:"medium",id:"you-handle-multipart-file",
     a:"Spring Boot auto-configures <code>MultipartResolver</code> for <code>multipart/form-data</code> uploads.<br><br><strong>Controller:</strong><br><pre>@PostMapping(\"/upload\")\npublic ResponseEntity&lt;String&gt; upload(@RequestParam(\"file\") MultipartFile file) {\n  if (file.isEmpty()) return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(\"No file\");\n\n  String fileName = file.getOriginalFilename();\n  String contentType = file.getContentType();\n\n  // Save to disk\n  Path dest = Paths.get(\"uploads/\").resolve(fileName).normalize();\n  file.transferTo(dest);\n\n  // Or upload to S3, save to DB, etc.\n  return ResponseEntity.ok(\"Uploaded: \" + fileName);\n}</pre><br><strong>Configuration limits:</strong><br><pre>spring.servlet.multipart.max-file-size=10MB\nspring.servlet.multipart.max-request-size=50MB</pre><br><strong>Security considerations:</strong><ul><li>Validate file extension and MIME type — never trust <code>contentType</code> from client</li><li>Sanitise file name — prevent path traversal (<code>../../etc/passwd</code>); use <code>.normalize()</code></li><li>Store outside the webapp root to prevent script execution</li><li>Scan for malware if accepting untrusted user uploads</li></ul><br><strong>Multiple files:</strong> <code>@RequestParam List&lt;MultipartFile&gt; files</code>"},

  {q:"What are Spring bean scopes — singleton, prototype, request, session?",d:"medium",id:"spring-bean-scopes-singleton",
     a:"Bean scope determines how many instances Spring creates and their lifecycle.<br><br><strong>singleton (default):</strong> one instance per Spring container — shared across all requests.<br><pre>@Component // default scope\npublic class ConfigService { }</pre><br><strong>prototype:</strong> new instance every time the bean is requested. Spring does not manage its destruction.<br><pre>@Component @Scope(\"prototype\")\npublic class OrderProcessor { }</pre><br><strong>request (web only):</strong> one instance per HTTP request. Lives until the request completes.<br><pre>@Component @Scope(\"request\")\npublic class RequestContext { }</pre><br><strong>session (web only):</strong> one instance per HTTP session. Lives until the session expires.<br><pre>@Component @Scope(\"session\")\npublic class ShoppingCart { }</pre><br><strong>application (web only):</strong> one instance per ServletContext (similar to singleton but tied to the webapp lifecycle).<br><br><strong>Injecting shorter scopes into longer ones:</strong> use <code>@Scope(proxyMode = ScopedProxyMode.TARGET_CLASS)</code> — Spring creates a proxy that resolves to the current request/session's instance at runtime."},

  {q:"How do you implement request/response logging for all HTTP calls?",d:"medium",id:"you-implement-request-response",
     a:"<strong>Option 1 — CommonsRequestLoggingFilter (built-in, basic):</strong><br><pre>@Bean\npublic CommonsRequestLoggingFilter requestLoggingFilter() {\n  CommonsRequestLoggingFilter filter = new CommonsRequestLoggingFilter();\n  filter.setIncludeQueryString(true);\n  filter.setIncludePayload(true);\n  filter.setMaxPayloadLength(10000);\n  filter.setIncludeHeaders(false); // avoid logging auth tokens\n  return filter;\n}\n// Enable: logging.level.org.springframework.web.filter.CommonsRequestLoggingFilter=DEBUG</pre><br><strong>Option 2 — Custom HandlerInterceptor (more control):</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class LoggingInterceptor implements HandlerInterceptor {\n  @Override\n  public boolean preHandle(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse res, Object handler) {\n    req.setAttribute(\"startTime\", System.currentTimeMillis());\n    log.info(\"[{}] {}{}\", req.getMethod(), req.getRequestURI(),\n      req.getQueryString() != null ? \"?\" + req.getQueryString() : \"\");\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  @Override\n  public void afterCompletion(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse res,\n      Object handler, Exception ex) {\n    long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - (Long)req.getAttribute(\"startTime\");\n    log.info(\"[{}] status={} time={}ms\", req.getMethod(), res.getStatus(), duration);\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Option 3 — Micrometer + Actuator /httptrace:</strong> automatically logs recent HTTP exchanges. Keep disabled in production (exposes request details)."},

  {q:"What is @DirtiesContext in Spring tests and when do you need it?",d:"medium",id:"dirtiescontext-spring-tests-you",
     a:"<code>@DirtiesContext</code> tells Spring to close and recreate the ApplicationContext after a test — expensive but necessary when a test pollutes shared state.<br><br><strong>When to use:</strong><ul><li>Test modifies an in-memory database that other tests depend on</li><li>Test mutates a singleton bean's state (cache, config, mock)</li><li>Test starts/stops embedded servers (Kafka, Redis) that leave threads running</li></ul><br><pre>@SpringBootTest\n@DirtiesContext(classMode = DirtiesContext.ClassMode.AFTER_EACH_TEST_METHOD)\npublic class OrderServiceTest {\n  @Test void test1() { orderRepo.deleteAll(); }\n  @Test void test2() { /* expects clean database */ }\n}</pre><br><strong>Performance impact:</strong> context startup can take seconds — avoid when possible:<ul><li>Use <code>@Transactional</code> on test methods — Spring rolls back after each test</li><li>Use <code>@MockBean</code> to replace beans without polluting context</li><li>Use test setup/teardown (<code>@BeforeEach</code>) to reset state explicitly</li></ul><br><strong>Scope options:</strong> <code>AFTER_EACH_TEST_METHOD</code>, <code>AFTER_CLASS</code>, <code>BEFORE_EACH_TEST_METHOD</code>, <code>BEFORE_CLASS</code>."},

  {q:"How does Spring Boot auto-configure DataSource and how do you override it?",d:"hard",id:"spring-boot-auto-configure",
     a:"Spring Boot auto-configures a <code>DataSource</code> bean based on classpath dependencies and <code>application.properties</code> — zero boilerplate for common cases.<br><br><strong>Auto-configuration trigger:</strong><br>If a JDBC driver is on the classpath (e.g., <code>postgresql</code>, <code>h2</code>), Spring Boot:<ol><li>Creates a <code>DataSource</code> using <code>spring.datasource.*</code> properties</li><li>Creates a <code>JdbcTemplate</code> bean</li><li>Runs <code>schema.sql</code> / <code>data.sql</code> if found on the classpath</li><li>Configures HikariCP connection pool (default)</li></ol><br><strong>Properties:</strong><br><pre>spring.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/orders\nspring.datasource.username=postgres\nspring.datasource.password=secret\nspring.datasource.hikari.maximum-pool-size=10\nspring.datasource.hikari.connection-timeout=30000</pre><br><strong>Override with a custom DataSource:</strong><br><pre>@Configuration\npublic class DataSourceConfig {\n  @Bean @Primary\n  public DataSource customDataSource() {\n    HikariDataSource ds = new HikariDataSource();\n    ds.setJdbcUrl(\"jdbc:postgresql://custom-host/db\");\n    ds.setUsername(\"user\");\n    ds.setMaximumPoolSize(20);\n    return ds;\n  }\n}</pre><br>Once you define your own <code>DataSource</code> bean, auto-configuration backs off via <code>@ConditionalOnMissingBean</code>."},

  {q:"What are the most important Spring, JPA, and validation annotations every senior backend developer should know?",d:"medium",id:"most-important-spring-jpa",
     a:"<strong>Spring Core DI/IoC:</strong><ul><li><code>@Component</code>, <code>@Service</code>, <code>@Repository</code>, <code>@Controller</code>, <code>@RestController</code> — stereotype annotations for component scanning</li><li><code>@Configuration</code> — marks a class as a source of bean definitions</li><li><code>@Bean</code> — registers a method's return value as a bean</li><li><code>@Autowired</code> — injects a dependency (prefer constructor injection)</li><li><code>@Qualifier</code> — disambiguates when multiple beans of the same type exist</li><li><code>@Primary</code> — marks the default bean when multiple candidates exist</li><li><code>@Lazy</code> — delays bean initialization until first use</li><li><code>@Scope</code> — defines bean scope (singleton, prototype, request, session)</li><li><code>@Value</code> — injects property values: <code>@Value(\"${app.name}\")</code></li><li><code>@ConfigurationProperties</code> — type-safe configuration binding</li></ul><br><strong>Spring MVC/REST:</strong><ul><li><code>@RequestMapping</code>, <code>@GetMapping</code>, <code>@PostMapping</code>, <code>@PutMapping</code>, <code>@DeleteMapping</code>, <code>@PatchMapping</code></li><li><code>@RequestBody</code>, <code>@ResponseBody</code>, <code>@PathVariable</code>, <code>@RequestParam</code>, <code>@RequestHeader</code>, <code>@CookieValue</code></li><li><code>@CrossOrigin</code> — configures CORS at method or class level</li><li><code>@RestControllerAdvice</code> + <code>@ExceptionHandler</code> — global exception handling</li></ul><br><strong>Spring Data/JPA:</strong><ul><li><code>@Entity</code>, <code>@Table</code>, <code>@Id</code>, <code>@GeneratedValue</code>, <code>@Column</code></li><li><code>@OneToMany</code>, <code>@ManyToOne</code>, <code>@OneToOne</code>, <code>@ManyToMany</code>, <code>@JoinColumn</code></li><li><code>@Query</code>, <code>@Modifying</code>, <code>@Transactional</code></li></ul><br><strong>Spring Transaction &amp; Async:</strong><ul><li><code>@Transactional</code> — manages transactions with configurable propagation, isolation, timeout</li><li><code>@Async</code> + <code>@EnableAsync</code> — async method execution</li><li><code>@Scheduled</code> + <code>@EnableScheduling</code> — scheduled tasks</li></ul><br><strong>Spring Security:</strong><ul><li><code>@EnableWebSecurity</code>, <code>@EnableMethodSecurity</code></li><li><code>@PreAuthorize</code>, <code>@PostAuthorize</code>, <code>@Secured</code></li></ul><br><strong>Bean Validation (JSR-380):</strong><ul><li><code>@Valid</code>, <code>@Validated</code>, <code>@NotNull</code>, <code>@NotBlank</code>, <code>@NotEmpty</code></li><li><code>@Size</code>, <code>@Min</code>, <code>@Max</code>, <code>@Email</code>, <code>@Pattern</code>, <code>@Past</code>, <code>@Future</code></li></ul><br><strong>Spring Testing:</strong><ul><li><code>@SpringBootTest</code>, <code>@WebMvcTest</code>, <code>@DataJpaTest</code>, <code>@MockBean</code></li><li><code>@Test</code>, <code>@BeforeEach</code>, <code>@AfterEach</code>, <code>@ParameterizedTest</code></li></ul><br><strong>Lifecycle &amp; Scoping:</strong><ul><li><code>@PostConstruct</code>, <code>@PreDestroy</code>, <code>@DependsOn</code>, <code>@Lookup</code></li><li><code>@Profile</code>, <code>@ConditionalOnProperty</code>, <code>@ConditionalOnClass</code>, <code>@ConditionalOnMissingBean</code></li></ul><br><br><strong>Example — JPA entity + controller showing annotations in context:</strong><br><pre>@Entity\n@Table(name = \"orders\")\npublic class Order {\n\n  @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)\n  private Long id;\n\n  @NotBlank @Size(max = 100)\n  @Column(nullable = false)\n  private String customerId;\n\n  @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"order\", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, fetch = FetchType.LAZY)\n  @NotEmpty\n  private List&lt;OrderItem&gt; items;\n\n  @Future\n  private LocalDate deliveryDate;\n}\n\n@RestController\n@RequestMapping(\"/orders\")\npublic class OrderController {\n\n  @PostMapping\n  @ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.CREATED)\n  public Order create(@Valid @RequestBody Order order) {\n    return orderService.save(order);\n  }\n}</pre>"}
);
